loration of welfare and healthcare during revolutionary and independent Ireland provides fresh and original insights into this critical juncture in Irish history. The book will appeal to Irish historians and those with interests in welfare, the Poor Law and the social history of medicine and institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic welfarexHistoryx20th centuryxIrelandxIreland. 0aPublic welfarezIrelandxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aIrish Free State.  aIrish Revolution.  aPoor Law Reform.  aboarded-out children.  ahospitals.  amother and baby homes.  aundeserving poor.  aunmarried mothers.  aworkhouses county homes.1 aLucey, Donnacha Seán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499673440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784996734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784996734/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles